WEBVTT

00:04.700 --> 00:05.048
.

00:05.092 --> 00:06.702
- You've reached
Dr. Helen Sharpe

00:06.745 --> 00:08.182
at NHS Hampstead.

00:08.225 --> 00:09.400
Please leave a message,
and I'll ring you back,

00:09.444 --> 00:11.272
no ifs, ands, or buts.

00:11.315 --> 00:12.490
[line beeps]

00:12.534 --> 00:14.666
- Voice mail
never sounded so good.

00:14.710 --> 00:16.625
Your diction is perfect.

00:16.668 --> 00:20.542
So long, embolic stroke.
Dr. Helen Sharpe is back.

00:20.585 --> 00:22.631
And I can't wait
to be back with you.

00:22.674 --> 00:24.850
Uh, I'm on my way
to meet the asset,

00:24.894 --> 00:29.116
and I think we're gonna send
Veronica packing for good.

00:29.159 --> 00:30.943
- You're fired.

00:30.987 --> 00:32.162
- Yeah.
I'm gonna call you back.

00:32.206 --> 00:34.730
Hi, there, Veronica. Sorry.

00:34.773 --> 00:36.079
You were saying something.

00:36.123 --> 00:37.385
- You know, I want you

00:37.428 --> 00:40.040
and your two-bit accomplices
out of here now.

00:40.083 --> 00:41.171
- Totally get that.

00:41.215 --> 00:42.955
Thing is,
in your haste to acquire UMI,

00:42.999 --> 00:45.610
you kind of forgot to read
the employee contracts that me

00:45.654 --> 00:47.177
and my two-bit accomplices
signed.

00:47.221 --> 00:48.874
It's funny--
I got a copy right here.

00:48.918 --> 00:53.357
Article 17 states that,
"Employees shall be safeguarded

00:53.401 --> 00:57.361
from termination
due to sale or merger."

00:57.405 --> 00:59.885
So I think
that's pretty clear.

00:59.929 --> 01:03.063
It's funny--it's kind of like
we planned it or something.

01:03.106 --> 01:06.240
I'll see you
at the company picnic?

01:06.283 --> 01:09.591
[clears throat]
Is the asset secure?

01:09.634 --> 01:11.941
- Patient room three.
- Great.

01:11.984 --> 01:16.206
[upbeat music]

01:16.250 --> 01:18.774
Sergeant Todd,
you sly son of a gun.

01:18.817 --> 01:22.517
♪

01:22.560 --> 01:24.214
- You said 0900.

01:24.258 --> 01:25.868
It's 0930.

01:25.911 --> 01:28.175
- Well, I'm usually
way later than that.

01:30.438 --> 01:32.222
Sorry, won't happen again.

01:32.266 --> 01:33.745
- So why all the subterfuge?

01:33.789 --> 01:35.791
- Well, I know that you
and I don't see eye to eye

01:35.834 --> 01:38.446
on most, if not all, aspects
of daily life.

01:38.489 --> 01:39.708
- Only because
you're a socialist.

01:39.751 --> 01:41.884
- And you are
a raging capitalist

01:41.927 --> 01:44.930
who--who has graciously come
to hear me out,

01:44.974 --> 01:46.280
so I'll get right to it.

01:46.323 --> 01:48.151
Um, what do you think
about Veronica Fuentes?

01:48.195 --> 01:51.111
- [clears throat] She is the
leader of this organization,

01:51.154 --> 01:52.112
and she has my support.

01:52.155 --> 01:54.549
- Yeah, but maybe...

01:54.592 --> 01:57.595
maybe you...
- Will that be all?

01:57.639 --> 01:59.249
- [sighs]

01:59.293 --> 02:01.947
Yeah. That'll be all.

02:01.991 --> 02:03.819
Dismissed.
[chuckles]

02:03.862 --> 02:07.344
Sorry. Sorry to have
wasted your time.

02:07.388 --> 02:11.261
- Dr. Fuentes is everything
I hate in a leader.

02:11.305 --> 02:13.045
She doesn't care
about you or me

02:13.089 --> 02:14.351
or anyone in this hospital.

02:14.395 --> 02:16.092
She's only
in the war for profit.

02:16.136 --> 02:19.791
♪

02:19.835 --> 02:21.315
- So...

02:21.358 --> 02:23.055
- If you are asking me

02:23.099 --> 02:25.275
if I would support
a regime change,

02:25.319 --> 02:27.930
the answer is yes.
- Todd.

02:27.973 --> 02:29.497
Yes!

02:29.540 --> 02:31.325
Sorry. Socialists like to hug.

02:31.368 --> 02:35.807
Um, okay, I think this is
the smoking gun

02:35.851 --> 02:37.418
that is gonna finally
bring Veronica down.

02:37.461 --> 02:40.943
These are financial records
for Urgent Medicine, Inc.,

02:40.986 --> 02:43.206
that Veronica just acquired.

02:43.250 --> 02:47.819
♪

02:47.863 --> 02:51.301
- My people at the DOJ will be
very interested in this.

02:51.345 --> 02:53.999
- Well, I was hoping
they might be.

02:54.043 --> 02:55.958
♪

02:56.001 --> 02:58.656
- The instructions
were no jewelry, Mum.

02:58.700 --> 03:00.876
- So what?

03:00.919 --> 03:02.791
Why you insist
on constantly meddling

03:02.834 --> 03:05.359
in my personal affairs
is beyond my comprehension,

03:05.402 --> 03:07.056
especially since,
as you so often remind me,

03:07.099 --> 03:08.231
I'm the worst mother.

03:08.275 --> 03:10.538
- My stroke was a wake-up call.

03:10.581 --> 03:12.496
In spite of how healthy
we may think we are,

03:12.540 --> 03:14.498
we must check
in with our bodies,

03:14.542 --> 03:15.847
and regular colonoscopy--

03:15.891 --> 03:17.327
- It's like you
want me to be ill,

03:17.371 --> 03:20.025
because doctor-patient
is the only relationship

03:20.069 --> 03:21.549
you understand.

03:21.592 --> 03:25.379
[distant indistinct chatter,
monitors beeping]

03:25.422 --> 03:28.773
- It's just
a routine colonoscopy, Mum...

03:28.817 --> 03:30.993
and I'll be with you
every step of the way.

03:31.036 --> 03:33.865
My face will be the first thing
you see when you wake up.

03:33.909 --> 03:35.432
- Brilliant.

03:35.476 --> 03:38.392
[soft music]

03:38.435 --> 03:40.132
♪

03:40.176 --> 03:41.786
- [sighs]

03:41.830 --> 03:45.225
♪

03:45.268 --> 03:47.444
- All right, then, Serwa.

03:47.488 --> 03:50.839
Will you count backwards
from ten for me, please?

03:50.882 --> 03:55.626
- Ten, nine, eight...

03:55.670 --> 03:57.846
sev...

03:57.889 --> 04:01.153
♪

04:01.197 --> 04:02.372
- [sighs]

04:02.416 --> 04:05.549
[engine rumbling]

04:09.336 --> 04:11.773
- Floyd?

04:11.816 --> 04:13.427
What are you doing
in Dad's car?

04:13.470 --> 04:15.211
- Driving it.

04:15.255 --> 04:16.560
- Because...?

04:16.604 --> 04:20.912
- I need your help
with something, Cort.

04:20.956 --> 04:22.392
- Does Mama know
you have that thing?

04:22.436 --> 04:24.264
- No. She doesn't
know anything yet.

04:27.354 --> 04:29.921
I'm gonna be a father.

04:31.488 --> 04:33.490
- Like, to a baby?

04:35.318 --> 04:38.234
- Yes, to a baby, but it...

04:38.278 --> 04:39.409
it's complicated.

04:39.453 --> 04:41.281
I'm--I'm gonna be involved

04:41.324 --> 04:44.240
but there's--
there's two more parents.

04:44.284 --> 04:45.807
The child has two other
parents,

04:45.850 --> 04:48.375
and that means my level
of contact might not be--

04:48.418 --> 04:50.028
- Wait, wait, wait, wait.

04:55.164 --> 04:56.948
You haven't told Mama
any of this, have you?

04:56.992 --> 04:59.081
- Mm-mm, no, no.
I wanted to come to you first.

04:59.124 --> 05:01.953
See if you had a line on Dad.

05:01.997 --> 05:03.955
- Who left our
mother swimming in debt

05:03.999 --> 05:06.131
with three children
to raise alone?

05:06.175 --> 05:07.655
No.

05:07.698 --> 05:09.309
I don't have a line
on that son of a bitch,

05:09.352 --> 05:10.527
and I don't want one.

05:10.571 --> 05:11.746
- Look,
if you don't know anything,

05:11.789 --> 05:12.877
then I got to talk to Mama.

05:12.921 --> 05:15.053
- No! No.

05:15.097 --> 05:18.100
You tell her
about your child out of wedlock

05:18.143 --> 05:20.450
and wanting to start
something with your father,

05:20.494 --> 05:22.757
you'll send her
to an early grave.

05:22.800 --> 05:25.281
Don't you say a word to her.

05:25.325 --> 05:28.284
[dramatic music]

05:28.328 --> 05:35.378
♪

05:37.075 --> 05:38.381
- Dr. Frome?
- Hey!

05:38.425 --> 05:40.340
- Everything okay?
- Yeah, yeah, fine.

05:40.383 --> 05:42.472
Just, um,
got a lot on my mind today.

05:42.516 --> 05:44.431
Um, have you seen Trevor?
Mr. Vaughan?

05:44.474 --> 05:46.389
- No. Would you like me
to page him?

05:46.433 --> 05:48.173
- No. No, no. That's okay.
Thank you.

05:48.217 --> 05:53.396
♪

05:53.440 --> 05:54.571
- Hey, boss.

05:55.920 --> 05:57.835
I was hoping to get some filing
under the belt

05:57.879 --> 05:59.924
before you got in.
- Oh, yeah, okay.

05:59.968 --> 06:02.492
Well, um,
I-I'll leave you to it.

06:02.536 --> 06:05.539
- Is everything all right?
- Hmm?

06:05.582 --> 06:09.369
- You're not still sketched out
about the other night, are you?

06:09.412 --> 06:12.284
- Uh, Trevor, I, uh...

06:12.328 --> 06:14.069
- Hey, nothing happened, Ig.

06:16.463 --> 06:18.029
It's only weird
because someone doped us.

06:18.073 --> 06:20.641
It's not our fault.
- [grunts softly]

06:20.684 --> 06:24.645
- So no harm, no foul,
all right?

06:24.688 --> 06:26.473
- Yeah. No harm, no foul.

06:26.516 --> 06:29.693
- Great. All right, then...

06:29.737 --> 06:31.565
have a good one.
- Okay.

06:31.608 --> 06:33.218
- You deserve it.

06:33.262 --> 06:39.529
♪

06:39.573 --> 06:41.226
- This your card?

06:41.270 --> 06:42.880
- No.

06:42.924 --> 06:45.100
- Oh, right. This is my card.

06:45.143 --> 06:47.232
Yours was
the seven of diamonds, right?

06:47.276 --> 06:49.713
- Right.
- Ah, yeah.

06:49.757 --> 06:51.976
It's on the ceiling.

06:52.020 --> 06:53.151
- What?

06:56.851 --> 06:59.375
How did you do that?
- Magic.

06:59.419 --> 07:02.465
Now check your pocket.

07:02.509 --> 07:05.729
- My brother Jace--
master of "cardistry."

07:05.773 --> 07:07.644
- The nerdy fruit
of a lonely childhood.

07:07.688 --> 07:09.124
- Oh.
- [chuckles]

07:10.691 --> 07:12.040
- Pick a card, Doc.

07:12.083 --> 07:14.042
- Uh, no, thanks.

07:14.085 --> 07:15.478
- Not a magic fan?

07:15.522 --> 07:17.480
- I prefer
to operate illusion-free.

07:17.524 --> 07:20.831
Uh, to that end,
Isla, your labs are in.

07:20.875 --> 07:23.355
And that pain you're feeling
in your stomach

07:23.399 --> 07:25.270
isn't from an ulcer.

07:25.314 --> 07:26.968
It's cirrhosis.

07:27.011 --> 07:28.360
- My liver?

07:28.404 --> 07:30.624
But I don't drink.
Neither of us do.

07:30.667 --> 07:31.929
Our mom was an alcoholic.

07:31.973 --> 07:33.583
- Yeah,
this isn't about drinking.

07:33.627 --> 07:35.280
The type
of cirrhosis you have is

07:35.324 --> 07:37.761
Alpha 1 Antitrypsin Deficiency.

07:37.805 --> 07:40.460
It's a genetic disorder.
- Is it treatable?

07:40.503 --> 07:42.157
- It is, but I'm afraid

07:42.200 --> 07:44.942
you will have to have
a liver transplant.

07:44.986 --> 07:47.510
Now, we can put you
on the UNOS list,

07:47.554 --> 07:51.079
but your best bet
would be your brother.

07:51.122 --> 07:53.081
If you're a match,
you could save her life.

07:55.344 --> 07:57.651
- Uh, yeah, uh...

07:57.694 --> 08:00.480
that's not gonna work.

08:00.523 --> 08:01.655
- What?

08:03.091 --> 08:04.484
He's joking.

08:04.527 --> 08:05.833
- I'm not.

08:07.530 --> 08:09.706
W-we have to find another way.

08:09.750 --> 08:14.798
♪

08:14.842 --> 08:16.191
- This is our son!
He's getting worse!

08:16.234 --> 08:18.541
- His school called us.
He was confused, dizzy.

08:18.585 --> 08:19.629
- Hey, can you tell me
your name?

08:19.673 --> 08:20.891
- [weakly] Darby.
- Heart rate's low.

08:20.935 --> 08:22.110
- Finger stick
blood sugar--12.

08:22.153 --> 08:23.633
- Okay, let's get him
to a room,

08:23.677 --> 08:24.852
and let's push
an amp of D50, now.

08:24.895 --> 08:25.896
- Uh, is he diabetic?

08:25.940 --> 08:27.158
On insulin?
- No.

08:27.202 --> 08:28.638
- Uh, any other meds
we should know about?

08:28.682 --> 08:30.161
- Just human growth hormone.

08:30.205 --> 08:32.076
He gets a shot from the school
nurse every day at lunch.

08:32.120 --> 08:34.383
- He can't see!
My son--he can't see.

08:34.426 --> 08:36.254
He's diabetic!
- Look at me.

08:36.298 --> 08:37.517
- Hey, buddy. You're okay.

08:37.560 --> 08:38.735
We're gonna take
good care of you, okay?

08:38.779 --> 08:41.172
- Hey, Kayden,
is it getting worse?

08:41.216 --> 08:44.001
[device beeps]
- Finger stick of 600.

08:44.045 --> 08:45.437
- He must have missed
his insulin.

08:45.481 --> 08:48.179
- No, Mom,
I told you I got my shot.

08:48.223 --> 08:50.181
- Let me guess--
from the school nurse?

08:50.225 --> 08:51.226
- Yes.

08:51.269 --> 08:52.923
- Do You know
a kid named Darby?

08:52.967 --> 08:55.535
- He's in Kayden's grade at
PS 441--how did you know that?

08:55.578 --> 08:57.188
- Uh, let's get him in a room,

08:57.232 --> 09:00.061
and let's start an IV
and 10 units of insulin Sub Q.

09:00.104 --> 09:01.932
- The school nurse
mixed up their medications.

09:01.976 --> 09:04.195
- Where are you going?
- To PS 441.

09:08.460 --> 09:08.635
.

09:08.678 --> 09:11.551
[indistinct chatter]

09:11.594 --> 09:14.162
- Excuse me, I'm looking
for the school nurse.

09:14.205 --> 09:15.598
- Do you have an appointment?

09:15.642 --> 09:17.208
- No, no,
I don't have a student here.

09:17.252 --> 09:21.125
I'm, uh, Dr. Max Goodwin
from New Amsterdam Hospital.

09:21.169 --> 09:23.040
And, uh,
we just admitted two boys

09:23.084 --> 09:25.782
who we believe were given the
wrong meds by the school nurse.

09:25.826 --> 09:27.479
- Oh, my God.

09:27.523 --> 09:29.525
Are you talking
about Kayden and Darby?

09:29.569 --> 09:30.613
- Yeah.

09:30.657 --> 09:33.224
- [sighs]
It--it was a mistake.

09:33.268 --> 09:35.923
People kept calling me
out to the desk, and I--

09:35.966 --> 09:37.098
I must have confused--

09:37.141 --> 09:39.796
[dramatic music]

09:39.840 --> 09:41.319
Are they gonna be okay?

09:41.363 --> 09:44.061
- Wait--
You're the nurse?

09:44.105 --> 09:50.981
♪

09:51.025 --> 09:54.115
- I'm the secretary.

09:54.158 --> 09:55.769
Because of budget cuts,

09:55.812 --> 09:58.815
we haven't had a licensed nurse
here for almost three years,

09:58.859 --> 10:00.164
so I've been subbing.

10:00.208 --> 10:02.079
- Do you have
any medical training?

10:02.123 --> 10:03.298
- No.

10:03.341 --> 10:05.474
But someone had to do it.

10:05.517 --> 10:07.955
- Did you report it
to the superintendent?

10:07.998 --> 10:09.173
- [scoffs]

10:09.217 --> 10:11.567
He's the one who authorized it.

10:13.308 --> 10:15.876
- Thank you
for taking the time, Dr. Frome.

10:15.919 --> 10:17.486
- Yeah, it's my pleasure.

10:17.529 --> 10:20.924
So Oncology forwarded me
your records, and, um...

10:20.968 --> 10:22.665
Well, first, let me just say

10:22.709 --> 10:24.449
that I have helped
many patients who've received

10:24.493 --> 10:26.538
the same diagnosis as you.

10:26.582 --> 10:29.367
And, uh, yeah,
it's a challenging time,

10:29.411 --> 10:32.457
but navigating
through our own mortality

10:32.501 --> 10:36.157
is always challenging.
- I'm not dying.

10:36.200 --> 10:40.074
- Oh. I'm sorry.
I thought, uh...

10:40.117 --> 10:42.859
I thought the cancer was, uh...
- Spontaneous recovery.

10:42.903 --> 10:44.208
- Yeah.

10:44.252 --> 10:47.908
- After three years,
I'm now officially...

10:47.951 --> 10:49.692
[sighs]
Cancer-free.

10:49.736 --> 10:52.042
- That's--I mean, that's--
that's incredible news.

10:52.086 --> 10:54.697
Congratulations.
- [crying] Uh-huh.

10:54.741 --> 10:56.568
- Oh.

10:56.612 --> 10:58.396
You know,
I would be willing to wager

10:58.440 --> 11:00.137
that most people who got
that kind of news

11:00.181 --> 11:02.705
would be overwhelmed with joy.

11:02.749 --> 11:06.361
But that's not quite
what I'm getting here, so...

11:06.404 --> 11:09.538
- When Dr. Schmidt first
told me I was in the clear

11:09.581 --> 11:12.193
and I wasn't going to die,

11:12.236 --> 11:14.456
I felt enormous relief.

11:14.499 --> 11:16.676
I couldn't wait
to tell my family.

11:16.719 --> 11:18.982
They had been with me
through the whole thing,

11:19.026 --> 11:20.723
taking care of me every day.

11:20.767 --> 11:22.464
- Support like that
can be invaluable.

11:22.507 --> 11:26.424
- Yes. But when I told them
that I wasn't going to die,

11:26.468 --> 11:29.732
I found out
how they really felt.

11:29.776 --> 11:32.039
- Which was?

11:32.082 --> 11:33.910
- [sighs]

11:33.954 --> 11:36.304
They actually wanted me dead.

11:37.958 --> 11:39.046
- Oh.

11:39.089 --> 11:41.222
♪

11:41.265 --> 11:43.354
- [sobbing]

11:43.398 --> 11:46.749
♪

11:46.793 --> 11:49.012
- How we doing over here?
- Daddy can come later.

11:49.056 --> 11:50.231
- Okay.

11:50.274 --> 11:52.450
- And I can go get your trains
at home.

11:52.494 --> 11:54.235
Do you want me to stay here?

11:54.278 --> 11:56.106
- Your friend's gonna be okay.

11:56.150 --> 11:57.368
- He is?
- Mm-hmm.

11:57.412 --> 11:58.848
- That sucks.

11:58.892 --> 12:00.937
- I'm sorry.

12:00.981 --> 12:02.939
Uh, what?

12:02.983 --> 12:05.768
- Kayden's not my friend.

12:05.812 --> 12:07.944
He's a bully.

12:07.988 --> 12:10.686
- Right. He's mean to you?

12:10.730 --> 12:12.209
- Oh, yeah.

12:12.253 --> 12:14.516
He talks down to me,

12:14.559 --> 12:17.127
tries to make me look stupid
in front of the other kids.

12:17.171 --> 12:18.825
- That's awful.

12:18.868 --> 12:21.175
- You watch.

12:21.218 --> 12:23.003
He'll probably just try
and blame me

12:23.046 --> 12:24.874
for what happened
with the nurse.

12:26.528 --> 12:28.660
- How exactly--
- Dr. Bloom?

12:28.704 --> 12:30.488
- Uh, not now.
- I was just wondering--

12:30.532 --> 12:31.794
- You're interrupting, Casey.

12:31.838 --> 12:33.622
Didn't I order labs, like,
an hour ago?

12:33.665 --> 12:35.667
- Yeah, but--
- So where are they?

12:35.711 --> 12:37.800
Thank you.

12:37.844 --> 12:39.410
I'm sorry about that.

12:39.454 --> 12:42.196
Um, so how exactly
does Kayden bully you?

12:42.239 --> 12:43.850
- Like that.

12:51.466 --> 12:54.817
- All right, I put your sister
on the UNOS list, but...

12:54.861 --> 12:56.427
it's a long wait.

12:56.471 --> 12:58.778
I don't know that
we'll get her a liver in time.

13:01.389 --> 13:04.218
- I can't help her.

13:04.261 --> 13:06.742
- Well, we won't know
until we test you.

13:06.786 --> 13:08.396
- [scoffs]

13:08.439 --> 13:11.529
It's not about
whether I'm a match, doctor.

13:17.013 --> 13:18.449
My liver's shot.

13:18.493 --> 13:24.020
♪

13:24.064 --> 13:25.630
I'm an alcoholic.

13:25.674 --> 13:28.242
I have been
since I was 13 years old.

13:30.374 --> 13:32.768
- But Isla said--
- She doesn't know.

13:32.812 --> 13:34.378
She's never known.

13:34.422 --> 13:36.424
Because of the hell
our mother put us through,

13:36.467 --> 13:38.861
we made a pact that we
would stay sober together.

13:38.905 --> 13:40.384
But I never could.

13:42.299 --> 13:44.736
- Wait, so you've been drinking

13:44.780 --> 13:47.348
since you were 13
and your sister doesn't know?

13:47.391 --> 13:50.307
- I'm drunk right now.

13:50.351 --> 13:51.918
Can you tell?

13:51.961 --> 13:56.618
No, because my tolerance
is off the chart.

13:56.661 --> 14:01.057
[scoffs] I've been fooling
everyone my entire life.

14:01.101 --> 14:04.887
[scoffs] My best trick.

14:04.931 --> 14:10.327
♪

14:10.371 --> 14:13.243
- Well, uh...

14:13.287 --> 14:15.158
I want to test you anyway.

14:15.202 --> 14:18.509
You may have a portion of your
liver that's still good.

14:21.034 --> 14:23.253
- If Isla finds out
that I've been lying to her

14:23.297 --> 14:25.168
after all these years,

14:25.212 --> 14:27.649
I will lose her forever.

14:27.692 --> 14:30.695
- Brother, you're gonna
lose her right now

14:30.739 --> 14:33.176
if you don't step up, Jace.

14:33.220 --> 14:36.353
Look, just let me test you...

14:36.397 --> 14:37.702
please.

14:39.313 --> 14:43.012
[monitor beeping rapidly]
- She's crashing.

14:43.056 --> 14:46.102
- ALS cart flying in.
- Right behind you.

14:46.146 --> 14:53.109
♪

14:53.153 --> 14:56.025
[indistinct chatter]

15:05.687 --> 15:07.471
- Welcome back, Mum.

15:07.515 --> 15:11.214
- Wait. It's happened?
It's over?

15:11.258 --> 15:14.087
- Yes. it's all done. See?

15:14.130 --> 15:16.524
Easy peas.

15:16.567 --> 15:18.352
- Dr. Sharpe?

15:18.395 --> 15:19.788
Can I talk
with you for a moment?

15:19.831 --> 15:22.834
- You will talk with me,
please.

15:24.010 --> 15:25.881
- Serwa...

15:25.925 --> 15:29.015
I'm afraid we found
multiple polyps in your colon

15:29.058 --> 15:32.801
that are malignant
and have metastasized.

15:32.844 --> 15:34.846
- Meaning?

15:34.890 --> 15:36.239
- If we had seen you earlier,

15:36.283 --> 15:38.459
I might be able to offer you
a different prognosis,

15:38.502 --> 15:41.462
but I'm afraid at this stage...

15:41.505 --> 15:43.420
your cancer is terminal.

15:43.464 --> 15:50.601
♪

15:56.999 --> 15:57.173
.

15:57.217 --> 15:58.740
- [grunts]

15:58.783 --> 16:00.829
- Nice serve.

16:00.872 --> 16:02.613
Are you Superintendent Davis?

16:02.657 --> 16:04.746
- [panting]

16:04.789 --> 16:06.443
You a parent?

16:06.487 --> 16:08.271
- I am. Yeah.

16:08.315 --> 16:10.186
But, fortunately,
my daughter's only three,

16:10.230 --> 16:12.275
so she doesn't attend any
of your schools.

16:12.319 --> 16:15.235
I'm also a doctor treating
two boys from PS 441

16:15.278 --> 16:17.019
who ended up in the hospital

16:17.063 --> 16:19.979
because your non-nurse
mixed up their meds.

16:23.025 --> 16:25.158
- I, uh...

16:25.201 --> 16:27.638
I didn't know about this.

16:27.682 --> 16:31.251
- I'm not surprised,
but I am curious why--

16:31.294 --> 16:34.080
why you would authorize
a secretary

16:34.123 --> 16:38.040
with no medical training
to hand out drugs to children.

16:39.824 --> 16:41.043
- How are the boys?

16:41.087 --> 16:43.263
- In the hospital...

16:43.306 --> 16:44.525
but stable.

16:45.787 --> 16:47.267
- [sighs]

16:47.310 --> 16:50.748
Look, it's not just PS 441,

16:50.792 --> 16:52.881
Dr. Goodwin.

16:52.924 --> 16:54.491
Even if I could come up
with the money,

16:54.535 --> 16:56.972
there are over 400
other schools in our district.

16:57.016 --> 16:59.105
- That don't have nurses?
- They used to--

16:59.148 --> 17:00.802
back in the day
when you and I went to school.

17:00.845 --> 17:03.283
We've had over
a billion dollars

17:03.326 --> 17:05.415
cut out of our budget
over the past decade.

17:05.459 --> 17:08.157
- So w-what happens
when a kid gets sick?

17:08.201 --> 17:10.246
- We treat them
as best as we can,

17:10.290 --> 17:13.467
and then we send them home,
often to an empty apartment.

17:13.510 --> 17:15.338
It's a disaster.

17:17.210 --> 17:19.038
I mean,
is your budget on the rise?

17:19.081 --> 17:21.301
You have any nurses
you can spare?

17:21.344 --> 17:23.868
Didn't think so.

17:23.912 --> 17:25.522
Look, I took an oath

17:25.566 --> 17:28.438
to make public schools better
for our children.

17:30.397 --> 17:32.529
I kept as many teachers
as I could,

17:32.573 --> 17:34.357
but something had to go.

17:34.401 --> 17:37.534
So now I come down here
every lunch break,

17:37.578 --> 17:41.799
and I imagine that each ball
is a bureaucrat

17:41.843 --> 17:45.107
who's taken something
important away from our kids.

17:45.151 --> 17:49.111
[dramatic music]

17:49.155 --> 17:51.983
- You want to hit one?

17:52.027 --> 17:53.507
- [sighs]

17:53.550 --> 17:56.075
- Okay, Mr. Fontenot, thank you
very much for coming in.

17:56.118 --> 17:57.641
I appreciate it.

17:57.685 --> 18:01.732
I, um--I had an interesting
session with your wife,

18:01.776 --> 18:03.778
um, but I realized
after speaking with Pauline

18:03.821 --> 18:06.085
that I really needed
to meet the entire family.

18:06.128 --> 18:08.174
- Oh?
- Yeah.

18:08.217 --> 18:11.220
You know, y-your wife
had a miraculous recovery.

18:11.264 --> 18:13.092
How has that made
everyone feel?

18:13.135 --> 18:16.051
- Oh, blessed.
- Relieved.

18:16.095 --> 18:17.835
- I just couldn't stop
hugging her.

18:17.879 --> 18:19.533
- I was beyond grateful.

18:21.056 --> 18:23.014
- Huh, okay.

18:23.058 --> 18:26.583
So, um, since Pauline found
out that she was cancer-free,

18:26.627 --> 18:30.761
has anyone noticed
that she was a tad depressed?

18:30.805 --> 18:33.590
- No. No.
- Not really.

18:33.634 --> 18:34.983
- Huh?

18:36.332 --> 18:37.942
- Okay.

18:37.986 --> 18:39.944
I used to love
watching the Spurs.

18:39.988 --> 18:41.032
They're my team, right?

18:41.076 --> 18:43.992
After Pauline
got her diagnosis,

18:44.035 --> 18:46.125
she'd always insist
we watch something else.

18:46.168 --> 18:48.431
I mean, how could I argue?
She had cancer.

18:48.475 --> 18:50.694
- But when I offer
to make her dinner,

18:50.738 --> 18:52.174
she always asks for fish.

18:52.218 --> 18:54.307
And most of us hate fish!

18:54.350 --> 18:55.960
- Could you believe it?

18:56.004 --> 18:58.180
She actually asked us
to go skydiving.

18:58.224 --> 19:00.139
And I'm terrified of heights.

19:00.182 --> 19:01.531
But I couldn't say no
to her

19:01.575 --> 19:03.142
because it's all
on her "bucket list."

19:03.185 --> 19:05.796
- After a while,
we all wanted cancer.

19:05.840 --> 19:07.320
- Um...

19:09.539 --> 19:11.062
- Huh.

19:11.106 --> 19:14.022
- [sighs] Yeah.

19:14.936 --> 19:18.244
Uh, your tests indicate
a severely damaged liver.

19:18.287 --> 19:21.812
85% scarred and cirrhotic.

19:21.856 --> 19:23.553
- [scoffs]

19:23.597 --> 19:26.513
So...I can't be a donor.

19:27.862 --> 19:29.211
- I'm afraid not.

19:29.255 --> 19:32.388
Our only option now
is to wait for one.

19:36.871 --> 19:39.047
- 85% unusable.

19:39.090 --> 19:41.049
That means 15% is good.

19:41.092 --> 19:42.485
Can't you use some of that?

19:42.529 --> 19:44.270
- Technically,
but that would leave you

19:44.313 --> 19:45.880
with a minimally
functioning organ.

19:45.923 --> 19:49.666
I mean, the slightest toxin
could kill you.

19:49.710 --> 19:53.192
I mean, you could never have
a drink again...

19:53.235 --> 19:55.019
you know, and given
your history,

19:55.063 --> 19:57.108
I don't think
that's a realistic path.

19:59.285 --> 20:05.421
♪

20:07.336 --> 20:09.425
- I can stop drinking.

20:10.557 --> 20:12.298
- [scoffs] Jace...
- I will.

20:12.341 --> 20:15.388
I have to for her...

20:15.431 --> 20:18.695
because if she goes...

20:18.739 --> 20:21.132
I'll be right behind her.

20:21.176 --> 20:26.399
♪

20:26.442 --> 20:28.966
- So blood sugar's leveled off
in both boys.

20:29.010 --> 20:32.187
- Yeah, I saw the labs.
- So...

20:32.231 --> 20:34.624
[chuckles] Am I a bully?

20:34.668 --> 20:36.104
- 100 %.

20:36.147 --> 20:37.714
Why?

20:37.758 --> 20:39.542
- 'Cause I don't want to be.
- [chuckles]

20:39.586 --> 20:42.676
Well, you may not want brown
eyes either, but, you know...

20:42.719 --> 20:46.157
- I mean, look, I know
I can be strong-willed, but...

20:46.201 --> 20:49.726
Me, I mean, a bully? Really?
- [laughs]

20:49.770 --> 20:52.686
Uh, Lauren, just listen to me,
all right?

20:52.729 --> 20:54.296
- Dr. Bloom, room seven.

20:54.340 --> 20:56.385
- It's Darby.

20:56.429 --> 20:57.821
[monitor beeping rapidly]

20:57.865 --> 20:59.345
- [coughing, choking]
- What's happening to him?

20:59.388 --> 21:00.998
- Run IV,
normal saline wide open.

21:01.042 --> 21:02.565
Start a second IV.
- On it.

21:02.609 --> 21:04.219
- Type and cross
a unit of red packed cells.

21:04.263 --> 21:05.394
- O-2 sats dropping.

21:05.438 --> 21:07.266
- I think he's choking
on his own blood.

21:07.309 --> 21:08.658
- Help him, please.
- Come on, Darby, come on.

21:08.702 --> 21:10.269
Stay with me.
Stay with me.

21:10.312 --> 21:13.750
- Mum, Mum, we are going
to deal with this.

21:13.794 --> 21:14.969
I'm gonna call people.

21:15.012 --> 21:16.840
There are loads of trials,
new medicines.

21:16.884 --> 21:18.973
I can get you in
to see the best of the best.

21:19.016 --> 21:20.104
And together we will--
- Enough!

21:20.148 --> 21:22.324
That is enough.

21:22.368 --> 21:23.934
- Mum, please.

21:23.978 --> 21:25.588
Please let me help you.

21:25.632 --> 21:28.461
Mum, where are you going?
- Home.

21:30.071 --> 21:32.987
[upbeat percussion playing]

21:33.030 --> 21:40.168
♪

21:42.997 --> 21:45.216
[laughter]

21:45.260 --> 21:47.175
♪

21:47.218 --> 21:49.177
- [sighs]

21:49.220 --> 21:56.227
♪

21:56.271 --> 21:58.926
[scattered cheers]

21:58.969 --> 22:00.667
- Mum...

22:00.710 --> 22:02.973
- Just watch.

22:03.017 --> 22:07.108
♪

22:07.151 --> 22:09.197
[laughter]

22:09.240 --> 22:15.377
♪

22:15.421 --> 22:18.075
- So this is home.

22:18.119 --> 22:20.643
- As close as
I can get for now.

22:20.687 --> 22:23.037
♪

22:23.080 --> 22:24.473
When I was a little girl,

22:24.517 --> 22:27.476
this dance, the kpanlogo,

22:27.520 --> 22:30.827
was something
only Ga-Adangbe did.

22:30.871 --> 22:32.960
- In Accra?

22:33.003 --> 22:37.704
- Young people cutting up--
my grandmother would sniff.

22:37.747 --> 22:40.489
In her mind, dancing
was only for praising God.

22:40.533 --> 22:43.666
But it brought me to life.

22:43.710 --> 22:47.322
We'd have to sneak
so she wouldn't catch us.

22:47.366 --> 22:48.758
When we moved to London,

22:48.802 --> 22:51.500
I thought I'd become
a professional.

22:51.544 --> 22:53.546
- You wanted to be a dancer?

22:53.589 --> 22:56.200
Why am I only just
hearing about this now?

22:56.244 --> 22:57.898
- I grew up.
Things change.

22:57.941 --> 22:59.856
- What changed?

22:59.900 --> 23:01.641
- I met your father.

23:01.684 --> 23:08.604
♪

23:14.218 --> 23:15.655
- Come on, Mum.

23:15.698 --> 23:21.008
♪

23:21.051 --> 23:22.052
Wote.

23:22.096 --> 23:28.972
♪

23:29.016 --> 23:31.192
[Serwa laughs]

23:31.235 --> 23:34.238
[all cheering]

23:34.282 --> 23:41.420
♪

23:43.900 --> 23:46.860
[dramatic music]

23:46.903 --> 23:52.822
♪

23:59.960 --> 24:00.177
.

24:00.221 --> 24:04.181
- Darby's gonna be okay.
- [sighs] What happened?

24:04.225 --> 24:06.140
- The bleeding was caused
by an ulcer in his stomach.

24:06.183 --> 24:09.012
We managed to stop the bleed,
so he's gonna be fine, but...

24:09.056 --> 24:11.014
- But we can't let
this happen again.

24:11.058 --> 24:13.713
Ah, look, we appreciate
you all coming down.

24:13.756 --> 24:15.976
After meeting
with your superintendent,

24:16.019 --> 24:18.500
I think I have a better idea
of how this happened.

24:18.544 --> 24:21.285
We've been dealing with
a shortage in nurses ourselves,

24:21.329 --> 24:23.505
and to combat
that problem,

24:23.549 --> 24:24.854
we've had to bring out a number

24:24.898 --> 24:26.377
of student nurses
and volunteers.

24:26.421 --> 24:27.727
- Can you send us one?

24:27.770 --> 24:29.206
- Well, we're hoping
to send you a whole bunch.

24:29.250 --> 24:31.121
- From where?
- From this room.

24:31.165 --> 24:33.254
- I'm sure many of you
are volunteering at the school

24:33.297 --> 24:34.081
in other ways.

24:34.124 --> 24:36.039
Uh, PTA, fundraising...

24:36.083 --> 24:37.867
- Yeah,
but no one here's a nurse.

24:37.911 --> 24:39.303
- You don't have to be.

24:39.347 --> 24:42.132
All you need is
some basic medical training.

24:42.176 --> 24:46.485
And, look, for those who
are willing, we can offer it.

24:46.528 --> 24:47.964
Here at New Amsterdam,

24:48.008 --> 24:50.532
you can become CNA's--
certified nursing assistants.

24:50.576 --> 24:52.360
- But many of us have jobs,
more than one.

24:52.403 --> 24:53.448
How could we--

24:53.492 --> 24:54.841
- Chipping in
just an hour a day,

24:54.884 --> 24:56.538
one day a week,
we can make this work.

24:56.582 --> 24:59.715
And we know it's not an ideal
situation, but it's a Band-Aid.

24:59.759 --> 25:01.543
And Band-Aids serve a purpose.

25:01.587 --> 25:04.807
They help keep things
together, so...

25:06.417 --> 25:07.767
So who's in?

25:09.333 --> 25:10.987
- [clears throat]

25:11.031 --> 25:14.295
[dramatic music]

25:14.338 --> 25:16.993
♪

25:17.037 --> 25:19.039
- You said
that during your illness,

25:19.082 --> 25:22.085
your family was always there
to support you, right?

25:22.129 --> 25:25.132
Always by your side?
- They were, yes.

25:25.175 --> 25:28.439
- Well, that's pretty easy
to get used to, isn't it?

25:28.483 --> 25:30.920
People doing what you want
whenever you want it--

25:30.964 --> 25:32.922
that's powerful stuff.

25:32.966 --> 25:36.230
But now that you're healthy,
it is important

25:36.273 --> 25:39.363
to give those same people the
space to attend to their needs.

25:39.407 --> 25:41.757
- [crying]

25:41.801 --> 25:44.107
- Pauline, why are you crying?

25:46.066 --> 25:48.547
- Because you're agreeing
with them.

25:48.590 --> 25:53.247
T-this is why they
don't want me around anymore.

25:53.290 --> 25:55.379
- Okay.

25:55.423 --> 25:57.033
Okay.

25:58.818 --> 26:00.863
Let me ask you this.

26:00.907 --> 26:02.604
Before the cancer,

26:02.648 --> 26:04.954
what would happen
if you didn't want to watch

26:04.998 --> 26:06.477
the Spurs game
with your husband?

26:06.521 --> 26:07.914
- We'd watch anyway.

26:07.957 --> 26:09.219
- And if you wanted fish

26:09.263 --> 26:10.873
and everybody else
wanted steak?

26:10.917 --> 26:12.092
- I'd eat steak.

26:12.135 --> 26:14.442
- Did you ever push back
on this?

26:14.485 --> 26:15.878
- I'd go along.

26:15.922 --> 26:18.794
- Your generation
was taught that it was rude

26:18.838 --> 26:21.101
to ask for what they wanted.

26:21.144 --> 26:24.931
When you got cancer
and you finally did ask for it,

26:24.974 --> 26:26.454
they gave it to you.

26:28.369 --> 26:32.634
That had to feel
pretty darn good, right?

26:32.678 --> 26:35.202
- More than good.

26:35.245 --> 26:39.728
It made me feel alive
for the very first time.

26:39.772 --> 26:41.556
- Well, that's ironic,
isn't it?

26:41.600 --> 26:44.994
- Huh.
- Considering you were dying.

26:45.038 --> 26:46.996
Pauline, you know, you spent

26:47.040 --> 26:49.520
your entire life
bending over backwards

26:49.564 --> 26:51.827
to support
the ones that you love,

26:51.871 --> 26:54.830
and then you
got sick with cancer,

26:54.874 --> 26:57.224
and those people
worked overtime

26:57.267 --> 26:59.052
trying to do the same for you
to support you.

26:59.095 --> 27:00.967
- I can't go
back to the way it was.

27:01.010 --> 27:03.317
- No, nor should you.

27:03.360 --> 27:05.754
But you need to figure out how
to take turns

27:05.798 --> 27:07.669
supporting each other now.

27:07.713 --> 27:09.105
Balance.

27:09.149 --> 27:11.760
And when that works,
do you know what we call it?

27:11.804 --> 27:13.501
Family.

27:13.544 --> 27:18.114
♪

27:18.158 --> 27:20.029
- Whoo!
[laughs]

27:20.073 --> 27:22.336
Now, that was fun.

27:22.379 --> 27:25.165
Oh, I've sweated
straight through my knickers!

27:25.208 --> 27:27.167
- Helen.
[both chuckle]

27:27.210 --> 27:29.386
You're not the only one.
- Right.

27:29.430 --> 27:32.520
So this is who you really are,
you little sneaker.

27:32.563 --> 27:34.522
All these years...

27:34.565 --> 27:37.699
- I once read that the
best gift you can give a child

27:37.743 --> 27:38.787
is to let them know you.

27:38.831 --> 27:40.920
- Yes.
Yes, Mum.

27:40.963 --> 27:43.487
- I didn't do that.

27:43.531 --> 27:45.098
- No.

27:45.141 --> 27:48.057
No, you most certainly did not.

27:48.101 --> 27:50.277
So I say
we bring extra knickers,

27:50.320 --> 27:52.975
and we make this
a regular once-a-week thing.

27:54.455 --> 27:56.370
- This was lovely today, Helen.
- Yes.

27:56.413 --> 27:58.502
- But this must remain mine.

28:03.029 --> 28:05.161
- [scoffs]

28:08.512 --> 28:11.864
Why must you
always shut me out?

28:11.907 --> 28:14.040
Honestly, it's...

28:14.083 --> 28:16.390
it's so confounding.

28:16.433 --> 28:19.001
[stammers]

28:22.135 --> 28:25.921
I mean, my marks
at school were always...

28:25.965 --> 28:29.882
"good but not perfect."

28:29.925 --> 28:32.275
Whenever I needed a hug,

28:32.319 --> 28:35.017
you would chide
that I was too needy.

28:35.061 --> 28:36.932
And you're always
going on and on

28:36.976 --> 28:38.499
about how much
you had to sacrifice

28:38.542 --> 28:41.328
so I could get
my fancy degrees, but now...

28:41.371 --> 28:43.460
now you won't even let me
use them to help you.

28:43.504 --> 28:45.201
I...

28:45.245 --> 28:48.030
[soft music]

28:48.074 --> 28:52.513
I can't keep begging you
to love me, Mum.

28:53.949 --> 28:56.952
- Child, you don't have to.
You have my love, always.

28:56.996 --> 28:59.346
- Please...
- It's true.

28:59.389 --> 29:04.003
It may not be how you want,
but it's there...

29:04.046 --> 29:06.745
in a gaze or a smile
when you're not looking.

29:06.788 --> 29:10.313
♪

29:10.357 --> 29:13.926
I marvel at what
you have become, Helen.

29:13.969 --> 29:16.929
♪

29:16.972 --> 29:18.669
You are magnificent.

29:18.713 --> 29:21.150
♪

29:21.194 --> 29:23.805
You are my greatest joy...

29:23.849 --> 29:26.808
♪

29:26.852 --> 29:29.071
And deepest pain.

29:29.115 --> 29:33.815
♪

29:33.859 --> 29:36.818
- [whimpers, cries]

29:36.862 --> 29:39.342
♪

29:39.386 --> 29:42.258
[sniffles, breathing heavily]

29:42.302 --> 29:49.439
♪

29:52.921 --> 29:55.184
Welcome back, Mum.

29:55.228 --> 29:58.144
[indistinct chatter,
monitor beeping]

30:00.537 --> 30:03.366
- Did it happen?
Is it over?

30:03.410 --> 30:06.543
- Yes, it's all done.
Everything went famously.

30:06.587 --> 30:10.330
- So, uh, as expected, you are
in blindingly good health.

30:10.373 --> 30:13.768
Clean as a whistle.
- Oh, Mum.

30:13.812 --> 30:16.640
What a relief.
L-let's get you some water.

30:19.774 --> 30:21.820
[monitor beeping,
indistinct chatter]

30:21.863 --> 30:24.170
- Healthy lobe
ready for transplant.

30:24.213 --> 30:26.520
- I'll get this
to Dr. Flores' OR.

30:26.563 --> 30:28.043
- Should do Isla quite well.

30:28.087 --> 30:29.392
And enough liver left over

30:29.436 --> 30:31.394
to sustain
a hopefully sober Jace.

30:31.438 --> 30:33.440
Let's go ahead
and close him up.

30:33.483 --> 30:35.877
Give me a 3-0 vicryl
on a needle driver.

30:35.921 --> 30:37.226
[monitor blaring rapidly]

30:37.270 --> 30:39.315
- Dr. Reynolds,
this doesn't look right.

30:39.359 --> 30:42.144
- Oh, no. What's left
of his liver...

30:42.188 --> 30:43.319
is dying.

30:43.363 --> 30:45.408
[dramatic music]

30:45.452 --> 30:47.193
Hepatic artery's hardened.

30:47.236 --> 30:49.978
Must be a blood clot that's
choking off the blood supply.

30:50.022 --> 30:52.633
Give me one milligram of TPA.

30:52.676 --> 30:59.379
♪

30:59.422 --> 31:01.337
Just give it a minute.

31:01.381 --> 31:04.253
[blaring continues]

31:04.297 --> 31:07.256
♪

31:07.300 --> 31:09.171
- It's getting darker.

31:09.215 --> 31:10.956
- It's gone.

31:10.999 --> 31:14.002
With no viable liver,
he won't clear anesthesia.

31:14.046 --> 31:15.786
He'll never wake up.

31:15.830 --> 31:18.746
[blaring continues]

31:18.789 --> 31:21.357
♪

31:21.401 --> 31:23.620
Close him up.

31:23.664 --> 31:26.449
Let's get him ready
for post op...

31:26.493 --> 31:30.410
so his sister can say goodbye.

31:30.453 --> 31:32.586
[elevator bell dings]

31:32.629 --> 31:34.022
- Hey, Max.

31:34.066 --> 31:37.112
So I just got word
that the DOJ is sending a bunch

31:37.156 --> 31:40.942
of FINCEN agents in order
to seize our financial records.

31:40.986 --> 31:42.552
- That's odd--maybe it has
something to do

31:42.596 --> 31:44.641
with your new acquisition.

31:44.685 --> 31:47.079
- Okay, you do not want to go
down this road.

31:47.122 --> 31:48.863
- You choose profit
over people,

31:48.907 --> 31:51.648
never care or compassion
or any of the principles

31:51.692 --> 31:52.998
that this hospital
was founded on.

31:53.041 --> 31:54.825
And if you had,
then maybe you would have done

31:54.869 --> 31:56.653
your due diligence.

31:56.697 --> 31:59.830
- Of what?
- Your new asset.

31:59.874 --> 32:03.138
UMI--it's a vast
money-laundering operation,

32:03.182 --> 32:04.792
and you bought it
with public funds.

32:04.835 --> 32:07.142
So now you have exposed
this hospital

32:07.186 --> 32:09.231
to some serious
criminal negligence.

32:09.275 --> 32:10.624
- No.

32:10.667 --> 32:13.496
You were running UMI,
so this is all on you.

32:13.540 --> 32:15.977
- [scoffs] I was just
a concerned employee

32:16.021 --> 32:17.152
who blew the whistle.

32:17.196 --> 32:19.241
Excuse me.

32:19.285 --> 32:21.940
- Max, look...

32:21.983 --> 32:23.332
just call off the feds,

32:23.376 --> 32:25.378
and I'll make you
co-medical director.

32:25.421 --> 32:26.814
- [scoffs] No, thanks.

32:26.857 --> 32:28.903
- Okay, then choose somebody
that you trust and--

32:28.947 --> 32:30.861
- Nope.

32:30.905 --> 32:33.603
- Max, I'll resign.

32:36.432 --> 32:39.479
♪

32:39.522 --> 32:40.697
You call off this raid,

32:40.741 --> 32:42.612
and I will walk
out of this building,

32:42.656 --> 32:44.440
and you will never, ever hear
a word from me again.

32:44.484 --> 32:47.356
- That's not enough.

32:47.400 --> 32:49.184
- What do you want from me?

32:49.228 --> 32:51.534
- What I want is for you

32:51.578 --> 32:54.798
to never run
another public hospital again.

32:54.842 --> 32:56.017
- Max.

32:56.061 --> 32:58.019
They're here.

32:58.063 --> 33:05.244
♪

33:18.735 --> 33:18.953
.

33:18.997 --> 33:21.129
- You sure I can't eat
real food?

33:21.173 --> 33:22.739
- Yeah, I'd take it easy
for a couple of days.

33:22.783 --> 33:25.525
No solids, only fluids.

33:25.568 --> 33:27.788
You're a tough kid, Darby.

33:27.831 --> 33:31.226
Don't let anyone tell you
any different, okay?

33:31.270 --> 33:34.925
[soft music]

33:34.969 --> 33:36.231
- Thank you, Dr. Bloom.

33:36.275 --> 33:38.799
- And, uh, some of us
got to talking...

33:38.842 --> 33:40.366
- We saw
how short-staffed you are,

33:40.409 --> 33:42.281
and you still went
the extra mile for our son.

33:42.324 --> 33:45.545
- So we figured
if you can do it, so can we.

33:45.588 --> 33:48.722
- You got your volunteers.

33:48.765 --> 33:51.594
♪

33:51.638 --> 33:54.728
[indistinct chatter]

33:57.644 --> 33:59.037
- Wow.

34:03.476 --> 34:05.608
- [sighs]

34:05.652 --> 34:08.089
Dr. Reynolds?

34:08.133 --> 34:10.004
[sighs]

34:10.048 --> 34:12.485
- Are you sure
your name isn't Lazarus?

34:12.528 --> 34:15.357
- What? Why?

34:15.401 --> 34:18.056
How's Isla?
- Oh, no, she's doing fine.

34:18.099 --> 34:21.363
But you, my friend,
you shouldn't be here.

34:21.407 --> 34:24.105
- Um, what's the trick?

34:24.149 --> 34:27.021
- I was certain
you weren't gonna wake up.

34:27.065 --> 34:29.284
Then your vitals
started improving,

34:29.328 --> 34:31.373
and so I just took this
and waved it over you,

34:31.417 --> 34:32.896
and, look, look at that.

34:32.940 --> 34:34.463
You see that there?

34:34.507 --> 34:36.509
That's an ectopic liver.

34:36.552 --> 34:39.555
That is a second liver
outside your old one.

34:39.599 --> 34:41.427
That's a rare genetic anomaly.

34:41.470 --> 34:43.516
That is hard to spot

34:43.559 --> 34:47.259
and one hell of a lucky break.
- [chuckles]

34:47.302 --> 34:49.739
- It's also why you managed
to drink so much over the years

34:49.783 --> 34:51.959
and not really feel
the effects.

34:52.002 --> 34:55.702
♪

34:55.745 --> 34:58.835
- Does Isla know
about my drinking?

34:58.879 --> 35:01.621
- No. Not yet.

35:01.664 --> 35:04.928
- So, technically,
with this second liver,

35:04.972 --> 35:07.975
I shouldn't have to tell her.
- Oh, man.

35:08.018 --> 35:11.065
♪

35:11.109 --> 35:14.329
Look, secrets aren't good
for any family, Jace.

35:14.373 --> 35:17.811
♪

35:17.854 --> 35:20.770
You believe in magic?

35:20.814 --> 35:23.730
- I believe I can get you
to believe in it.

35:23.773 --> 35:25.906
Illusions don't come
from magic.

35:25.949 --> 35:29.170
They come from hours
and hours of work.

35:29.214 --> 35:32.086
- That's right.
Right, so...

35:32.130 --> 35:35.089
magic is just putting
in the time

35:35.133 --> 35:38.048
to create a miraculous result.

35:38.092 --> 35:40.007
And I would imagine that

35:40.050 --> 35:42.879
getting sober's a lot
like that, too.

35:42.923 --> 35:44.968
And, hey,
since you've already proven

35:45.012 --> 35:47.319
that you can put in the time...

35:49.103 --> 35:51.497
I'd lean into the truth

35:51.540 --> 35:54.021
and see what kind of magic
that can bring.

35:54.064 --> 36:00.680
♪

36:00.723 --> 36:02.116
[sighs]

36:02.160 --> 36:04.031
- The good news is,
you will not have to have

36:04.074 --> 36:05.859
another one of those
for ten years.

36:05.902 --> 36:08.470
We do, however, need to get you
scheduled in for a mammogram.

36:08.514 --> 36:10.907
- The NHS has an array
of perfectly adequate doctors

36:10.951 --> 36:12.605
my GP can refer me to.

36:12.648 --> 36:14.998
- But, Mum--
- Helen...

36:15.042 --> 36:17.479
I know you love me.

36:17.523 --> 36:20.047
You don't have to keep trying
to prove it.

36:21.788 --> 36:23.529
Walk with me.

36:25.400 --> 36:26.619
- Where?

36:26.662 --> 36:29.056
- There's this place
I'd like to show you.

36:31.754 --> 36:33.843
Wote.

36:33.887 --> 36:37.151
- ♪ Speechless

36:37.195 --> 36:41.199
♪ I wonder if you feel...

36:41.242 --> 36:43.592
- Hey. I'm out, Ig.
Have a good night.

36:43.636 --> 36:45.333
- Uh, yeah, Trevor, hang on.

36:45.377 --> 36:47.205
Would you mind?
Can we--can we talk a second?

36:47.248 --> 36:49.076
- Uh-oh.
[chuckles]

36:49.119 --> 36:51.078
Of course.
What's up?

36:51.121 --> 36:52.993
- Um...
[clears throat]

36:53.036 --> 36:55.822
You were--you were
very gracious this morning.

36:55.865 --> 36:57.998
Um, but I--

36:58.041 --> 36:59.608
I have to be real with you.

36:59.652 --> 37:01.306
I have been seeing a therapist,

37:01.349 --> 37:05.266
and I've been trying to repair
damage done to my marriage.

37:05.310 --> 37:08.965
I've let the attention that
you give me get into my head,

37:09.009 --> 37:12.317
and it has started to affect...

37:12.360 --> 37:14.841
my relationship with my family.

37:14.884 --> 37:17.409
- Oh, man, I'm--I'm sorry.
- Yeah.

37:17.452 --> 37:21.674
I have a lot of work
to do on myself.

37:21.717 --> 37:23.110
And I don't think...

37:23.153 --> 37:28.158
♪

37:28.202 --> 37:29.943
I can't work with you anymore.

37:29.986 --> 37:32.598
♪

37:32.641 --> 37:34.295
And so I'm going to call HR--

37:34.339 --> 37:36.515
- You're gonna call HR?
Why are you gonna call HR?

37:36.558 --> 37:39.300
- Uh, nothing, I'm just
gonna tell them the truth.

37:39.344 --> 37:42.216
I'm gonna tell them that
I hired a very qualified nurse

37:42.260 --> 37:44.610
who I have chemistry with

37:44.653 --> 37:47.526
and who's attention
I have clearly been enjoying

37:47.569 --> 37:49.092
in an inappropriate way

37:49.136 --> 37:51.791
and that it's not healthy

37:51.834 --> 37:54.359
for anybody.

37:54.402 --> 37:56.448
- [scoffs]
Hasn't my work been any good?

37:56.491 --> 37:58.885
- Your work
has been fine, Trevor.

37:58.928 --> 38:00.147
- [scoffs]

38:00.190 --> 38:02.410
♪

38:02.454 --> 38:04.586
It's not why
you hired me, is it?

38:04.630 --> 38:07.720
♪

38:07.763 --> 38:09.156
- No, no.

38:09.199 --> 38:12.855
- [scoffs, sighs]

38:12.899 --> 38:19.993
♪

38:22.125 --> 38:24.563
Everybody thinks
you are such a nice guy,

38:24.606 --> 38:25.999
but you're not, are you?

38:26.042 --> 38:32.614
♪

38:32.658 --> 38:34.442
I quit.

38:34.486 --> 38:38.751
♪

38:38.794 --> 38:41.754
[door opens, slams]

38:41.797 --> 38:45.497
♪

38:45.540 --> 38:48.543
- [sighs]

38:48.587 --> 38:52.721
♪

38:52.765 --> 38:54.027
- Hey.

38:54.070 --> 38:59.075
♪

38:59.119 --> 39:02.122
Hey. What's up?

39:02.165 --> 39:04.429
- I'm really sorry
for bullying you.

39:04.472 --> 39:05.865
- What?

39:05.908 --> 39:08.215
Oh, no, no, no--
- I mean, I had no idea.

39:08.258 --> 39:09.651
- No, Lauren, I--
- No, listen to me, okay?

39:09.695 --> 39:11.044
I...

39:11.087 --> 39:14.264
I had a real problem
with this when I was a kid.

39:14.308 --> 39:16.441
I mean, I was not nice.

39:16.484 --> 39:18.965
I had a lot of anger
towards my mother,

39:19.008 --> 39:21.184
and I took it out
on the other kids.

39:21.228 --> 39:23.970
Then as I got older,
I just--

39:24.013 --> 39:25.711
I thought I'd moved past it,
you know?

39:25.754 --> 39:27.800
- You have.
- Well, clearly, I haven't.

39:27.843 --> 39:29.410
I mean, you said so yourself.

39:29.454 --> 39:31.456
- [laughing]

39:31.499 --> 39:35.547
Lauren, uh,
I was messing with you.

39:37.331 --> 39:38.985
- You were?
- Yeah!

39:39.028 --> 39:40.943
Yeah, you're not a bully.

39:40.987 --> 39:45.339
You're bossy, super impatient,
moody, temperamental.

39:45.383 --> 39:47.385
I can go on and on,
but the point is,

39:47.428 --> 39:49.256
is that bullies go out
of their way to hurt people.

39:49.299 --> 39:51.476
They prey on the vulnerable.

39:51.519 --> 39:56.219
You lift people up--
Brunstetter, Leyla, Walsh...

39:56.263 --> 39:58.047
me.
[chuckles]

40:00.876 --> 40:02.922
- You were joking?

40:02.965 --> 40:06.447
- Hey. Hey, come on, now--
- Well, it wasn't funny, okay?

40:06.491 --> 40:08.536
- Listen, you set me up. I--
- Get out of here, okay?

40:08.580 --> 40:10.364
Get out of here...
- Okay.

40:10.408 --> 40:12.627
- Before I actually get mad
and start yelling!

40:12.671 --> 40:14.237
- It was a little funny.

40:14.281 --> 40:16.196
A little funny--
un poquititofunny.

40:16.239 --> 40:17.632
- Mm-hmm.
- Un poco,a little bit.

40:17.676 --> 40:19.852
- Nope.
- A little funny. You laughed.

40:19.895 --> 40:21.723
You're laughing now.

40:21.767 --> 40:24.987
See you later, boss!
- [mutters, sniffles]

40:25.031 --> 40:26.467
Oh, God.

40:26.511 --> 40:28.774
- [inhales deeply]
Hey.

40:30.950 --> 40:32.125
Sorry, I know you're sleeping

40:32.168 --> 40:34.997
I just wanted to tell you
that, uh, it's...

40:35.041 --> 40:36.651
it's over.

40:36.695 --> 40:38.131
[chuckles]

40:38.174 --> 40:41.090
I'm coming home.

40:41.134 --> 40:44.529
And I can't wait to wrap
my arms around you.

40:44.572 --> 40:47.619
Uh, I'm gonna call you back,
but I love you.

40:47.662 --> 40:48.576
Todd!

40:48.620 --> 40:50.883
Are the, uh, agents still here?

40:50.926 --> 40:52.362
- No.
They left.

40:52.406 --> 40:54.887
- Oh, well, I just wanted
to thank them and you for--

40:54.930 --> 40:57.716
- Actually,
they wanted me to thank you...

40:57.759 --> 40:59.848
for alerting
them to this issue.

41:01.894 --> 41:03.112
- What?

41:04.462 --> 41:07.552
- They're concluding
the investigation.

41:07.595 --> 41:09.423
It seems they are going
to monitor

41:09.467 --> 41:11.730
the situation going forward.

41:11.773 --> 41:13.949
- But they're shutting down
UMI, right?

41:13.993 --> 41:17.344
I mean, they're making arrests?
This is fraud.

41:17.387 --> 41:19.825
Our shareholders--
- Someone called them off.

41:23.002 --> 41:24.525
- [stammers]
Uh...

41:24.569 --> 41:28.921
You--you read
the documents, right?

41:28.964 --> 41:32.620
I mean, am I...crazy?

41:32.664 --> 41:34.056
This is criminal.

41:34.100 --> 41:38.321
- Do you know who owns
the other franchises of UMI?

41:40.585 --> 41:41.760
Right.

41:41.803 --> 41:43.413
And you never will

41:43.457 --> 41:46.242
because UMI is too big.

41:46.286 --> 41:48.244
It's in all 50 states.

41:48.288 --> 41:51.639
It's owned by politicians,
corporations,

41:51.683 --> 41:53.032
even doctors.

41:53.075 --> 41:55.861
Everyone is making a profit,

41:55.904 --> 41:58.820
and it seems everyone is
willing to look the other way

41:58.864 --> 42:01.214
to keep the profits flowing.

42:03.521 --> 42:05.348
- So what are we supposed
to do now?

42:05.392 --> 42:08.351
[tense music]

42:08.395 --> 42:11.659
♪

42:11.703 --> 42:15.402
- Well, you can start
by getting out of my office.

42:15.445 --> 42:19.319
♪
